There is no comparison between this Whole Foods Market located near South Park Mall (one of my favorites) and the one in Huntersville. Most of the employees go over & above to make sure you're happy at this location. If you're a Whole Foods devoted customer like we are and you visit Charlotte, you'll have to stop by to experience the difference.

My very first time ever visiting a Whole Foods Market, I was very impressed with the quality of products as well as the cleanliness of the store. The personnel was very helpful and friendly and helped me locate exactly what I needed. Everything was very fresh and the prices were very reasonable as well. I will definitely be returning

This Whole Foods was really disappointing. The produce section was almost bare and what they did have was moldy and rotten. I ended up doing  a smaller shop and had to stop elsewhere afterwards. I am lactose intolerant and the vegan dairy selection was slim and difficult to find. I also don't think anyone buys it from there so the quality of the products was off. This Whole Foods was in a beautiful neighborhood but I will not be returning on my next trip to NC, simply just wasn't worth it.

I live about a block away in the same complex at ashley park lane.  I find this store is very convenient for me when I need a couple of things and I don't mind the prices. The store is very clean and the shelves are very neat. I also find some of the brands interesting because I have never seen them before and I try them out sometimes. I am learning to venture out more and open up my world a little bit.
I shop at Aldi for the big bulk paper products, meats, fish, fruits and vegetables. When I need to get something specific I can always find it at Harris Teeter or Compare.
I am originally from NY and have been here over a year now. What I find interesting about Whole Foods is the interaction with the staff. Half the staff is nice and friendly and customer centric. If you are looking for a product they will let you know where it is located, if they changed it to another aisle, or if they are out and what stores near-by may carry it.
I find this is a plus because it is a sign of a good company and a well trained staff.
The other half looks annoyed to be there, and act like they are suffering through some kind of punishment. Sometimes I look at them in the eyes and they avoid any kind of interaction. A simple and friendly hello would be enough for me.
This is what I call a friendly light place and maybe it is a Charlotte thing. They are polite but they really don't want any kind of interaction with other people. I get it because that is how NY people are. We are are always in a rush to catch a train, bus, or cab to and from work and the people that get in our way are just annoying.
I know this is a rough job market, but why on earth would you take a job dealing directly with the public if you don't really enjoy being around people.

Every time I buy berries in a pack here they are moldy already. I even open the pack to see, but unless I root through the berries in the store I can't tell that there's a layer of mold right under the surface. For the prices, the produce should really be fresh.
The vegan sandwich from deli was great.

They are expensive.  I only come here to get things that are not available elsewhere. Decaffeinated tea that use the CO2 process; Bronner's bar soap(fragrance free), Trader Joe's carries the peppermint and sells it for about $1 less, but its too strong for my skin.
The uptown one has better food though
Quality foods are available

Whole foods prices are just on a WHOLE other level. Crazy how much they charge when half of their inventory is the same as Publix or Harris Teeter. They do carry Brunost - brown cheese from Norway which is delicious. Highly recommend for your waffles. They have it a few dollars cheaper than Publix

Love all their products but everyone says they don't shot there often because of their prices. If they don't lower their prices they might end up like Earth Fair. Not sure how they don't understand that they would get at least twice as many costumers if they lowered their prices, especially now that they are working with Amazon and amazon offers similar products for half the price. Just paid almost $4 for 6 fresh tiny Russian tea cookies. It's just too much, but no one else carries them around here. I love their products that no one else has. Just wish they wouldn't make us go broke for them. We shouldn't have to splurge for groceries and natural medicine/hygiene products.
